200
00:22:53,191 --> 00:22:56,358
And it can be a real pain.

201
00:22:57,402 --> 00:23:10,836
So, you know, the example I give is that somebody's ill, so you take them grapes and soup or something, you know, and they say, you know, thank you very much, but I really couldn't eat this soup, you see.

202
00:23:11,436 --> 00:23:15,661
And inside your mind you say, you know, I've just spent two hours making this bloody soup.

203
00:23:17,663 --> 00:23:19,164
They say, you could do something for me.

204
00:23:19,586 --> 00:23:20,747
Oh, yeah, very good.

205
00:23:20,767 --> 00:23:21,907
Could you clean my toilet?

206
00:23:23,692 --> 00:23:27,757
I think I better clean your toilet.

207
00:23:27,777 --> 00:23:31,821
I came here to offer you soup.

208
00:23:31,842 --> 00:23:38,489
So you can always catch yourself when you're doing this good and then you find actually you're being a do-gooder.

209
00:23:40,250 --> 00:23:42,113
So how do we get beyond that?

210
00:23:42,192 --> 00:23:42,834
It's very simple.

211
00:23:42,874 --> 00:23:44,275
You ask the person what they want.

212
00:23:46,597 --> 00:23:48,839
You don't presume on anything at all.

213
00:23:51,435 --> 00:23:55,280
So giving itself is a really...

214
00:23:56,042 --> 00:23:58,786
Generosity is really crucial in our practice.

215
00:23:59,527 --> 00:24:01,711
And it's a form of love, of course.

216
00:24:01,830 --> 00:24:05,015
Generosity is just there.

217
00:24:06,277 --> 00:24:12,766
And it's lovely when you see these... What do they call it?

218
00:24:12,786 --> 00:24:13,647
Sports for...

219
00:24:14,828 --> 00:24:15,549
Sport relief.

220
00:24:15,851 --> 00:24:17,732
Yeah, sport relief and comic relief.

221
00:24:17,993 --> 00:24:19,234
They raise masses of money.

222
00:24:19,556 --> 00:24:21,038
And it's really quite...

223
00:24:21,625 --> 00:24:28,314
Well, it's quite uplifting to know that people are prepared to, you know, to give, you know, for these causes.

224
00:24:28,374 --> 00:24:28,973
Really wonderful.

225
00:24:32,798 --> 00:24:37,184
So that sort of covers three of them anyway.

226
00:24:37,204 --> 00:24:42,692
So it's the giving and the, I mean, gratitude isn't mentioned here, but it's definitely something.

227
00:24:43,173 --> 00:24:48,138
Meister Eckhart, whom some of you might know, the 13th century mystic, who's very close to Buddhism,

228
00:24:48,607 --> 00:24:51,853
If you read his stuff, it's very, very close to the Buddha's understanding.

229
00:24:53,055 --> 00:24:58,884
He says, if you were to say thank you all the time, that would be enough.

230
00:24:58,904 --> 00:25:03,993
That's how important he thought gratitude was.

231
00:25:04,375 --> 00:25:05,276
Brian does it, doesn't he?

232
00:25:05,296 --> 00:25:06,778
Just for today I will be thankful.

233
00:25:07,900 --> 00:25:12,167
Even he's caught on to it.

234
00:25:12,828 --> 00:25:14,211
So it's something to reflect on.

235
00:25:15,794 --> 00:25:17,096
So we've done the renunciation.

236
00:25:17,135 --> 00:25:27,627
Renunciation is, you know, and it's just catching yourself these sneaky little selfishnesses.

237
00:25:29,871 --> 00:25:33,634
You know, where you take just the bigger piece of cake.

238
00:25:33,855 --> 00:25:34,635
You know what I mean?

239
00:25:35,477 --> 00:25:43,266
You take that extra toffee, you know, and just catch yourself.

240
00:25:43,286 --> 00:25:44,788
And then you hate the person who gets it, of course.

241
00:25:47,941 --> 00:25:49,843
So, renunciation.

242
00:25:51,324 --> 00:25:53,606
Morality, well, we've talked a lot about that.

243
00:25:56,569 --> 00:26:06,239
It's again, morality here, the Buddha's actually meaning just the basic things that you determine, not to go there, that's all.

244
00:26:06,259 --> 00:26:07,941
Wisdom, well, we've talked about that.

245
00:26:08,301 --> 00:26:12,526
So this is more of a mental, of a mind.

246
00:26:12,586 --> 00:26:14,708
So a lot of these are heart things, like giving.

247
00:26:15,515 --> 00:26:17,037
And renunciation and patience.

248
00:26:17,477 --> 00:26:18,738
But wisdom is coming from.

249
00:26:18,778 --> 00:26:20,220
This wisdom within us.

250
00:26:21,201 --> 00:26:22,541
This understanding.

251
00:26:22,582 --> 00:26:23,623
The faculty of wisdom.

252
00:26:23,923 --> 00:26:25,525
Which is not to be confused with intellect.

253
00:26:25,565 --> 00:26:25,924
Remember.

254
00:26:28,508 --> 00:26:29,388
There's a lovely story.

255
00:26:29,409 --> 00:26:31,730
I always forget the name of the monk.

256
00:26:32,192 --> 00:26:34,193
But in those days remember.

257
00:26:34,574 --> 00:26:35,535
They didn't write things down.

258
00:26:35,575 --> 00:26:36,296
They remembered them.

259
00:26:37,156 --> 00:26:39,338
And this poor monk he said.

260
00:26:39,398 --> 00:26:42,142
When he learnt a new stanza.

261
00:26:42,362 --> 00:26:43,784
Of the Buddha's teachings.

262
00:26:43,804 --> 00:26:45,285
It would knock the one he's just learnt.

263
00:26:45,535 --> 00:27:14,326
out of his head so his brothers advised him to leave the monastic life said you know you're not going to get anywhere so the Buddha hearing this went to see him and he gave him a very simple exercise of rubbing a piece of cloth and wiping his face with a clean cloth and just saying impermanence impermanence impermanence and he became fully liberated just like that it didn't work for everybody it didn't work for me

264
00:27:14,999 --> 00:27:20,246
But it's a different faculty.

265
00:27:20,266 --> 00:27:21,166
It's not the intellect.

266
00:27:21,247 --> 00:27:24,131
It's not about understanding something.

267
00:27:24,371 --> 00:27:28,797
There's one man called Putika.

268
00:27:28,817 --> 00:27:29,417
What's his name?

269
00:27:29,959 --> 00:27:31,119
Empty Putika.

270
00:27:32,061 --> 00:27:37,147
There's another monk and he can explain the Dharma wonderfully.

271
00:27:37,528 --> 00:27:39,971
But the Buddha calls him Empty Putila.

272
00:27:39,991 --> 00:27:40,393
Empty.

273
00:27:40,833 --> 00:27:42,275
Because he's not coming from experience.

274
00:27:42,315 --> 00:27:43,317
He's coming from his intellect.

275
00:27:43,336 --> 00:27:44,397
He's coming from understandings.

276
00:27:45,728 --> 00:28:15,583
and people like that really have a big problem because they really believe that because they've really understood something that therefore they've actually truly experienced it so that's a lot to do with our honesty as well you see there's another little story about a teacher and all his students become fully liberated

277
00:28:16,525 --> 00:28:17,045
And he isn't.

278
00:28:17,306 --> 00:28:19,146
And he thinks, oh, I can't understand this.

279
00:28:21,088 --> 00:28:27,474
And so he goes off and he asks them, you know, he said, you know, do you think you could help me?

280
00:28:27,895 --> 00:28:30,979
And what the student realises is that his teacher's very conceited.

281
00:28:32,000 --> 00:28:34,501
So he says, well, I can't really help you.

282
00:28:34,541 --> 00:28:36,923
Why don't you go and see somebody else?

283
00:28:37,305 --> 00:28:41,448
Eventually, one of his students tells him to go and see this little boy.

284
00:28:41,508 --> 00:28:46,313
So you can imagine that's a bit humiliating, you know, how to become liberated.

285
00:28:46,816 --> 00:28:49,500
So the little boy takes him off to an anthill.

286
00:28:49,519 --> 00:28:52,805
Now, in the east, when the ants have left, it's often the abode of a snake.

287
00:28:54,267 --> 00:29:03,821
And so the little boy says, if a snake lives in that anthill and there are six holes, how do you get him to come out?

288
00:29:05,984 --> 00:29:09,851
And he said, well, you just stop up five holes and he'll come out through the sixth.

289
00:29:10,371 --> 00:29:11,472
He said, that's what you've got to do.

290
00:29:12,247 --> 00:29:21,075
In other words, through the senses, the six senses, by stopping five senses and just watching the mind, then you begin to understand, you see.

291
00:29:21,214 --> 00:29:26,680
Well, of course, as all these stories go, in no length of time, the teacher was fully liberated.

292
00:29:29,221 --> 00:29:33,086
So, don't get confused with understanding.

293
00:29:33,105 --> 00:29:35,607
The Buddha actually talks about three levels of understanding.

294
00:29:35,929 --> 00:29:40,853
The level of just hearing something, being inspired by it, understanding it,

295
00:29:41,186 --> 00:30:11,076
but unable really to repeat it because it's not become your own intellectual knowledge and then once it has become your own understanding you can talk about it but then at a deeper level it has to be realised so you can talk about impermanence till the cows come home but have we actually experienced it at the level of me arising and passing away so that's the wisdom bit yeah

296
00:30:11,713 --> 00:30:18,426
Energy, energy, what's the other word, effort.

297
00:30:19,789 --> 00:30:21,993
Yeah, you've got to be careful with this effort business.

298
00:30:22,434 --> 00:30:33,537
Remember that, normally speaking, our effort is in trying to do something, trying to achieve something, which is perfectly alright in the world.

299
00:30:34,394 --> 00:31:03,844
but when we come to our meditation it's important to realize that the effort is just to be aware once you start looking for something or trying to attain something then you normally end up in a hole because even if you're not fully aware of it there is some concept at the back of the mind driving this sense of wanting to achieve something so be careful with effort

300
00:31:04,751 --> 00:31:05,913
Just keep reminding yourself.

301
00:31:06,433 --> 00:31:08,557
My teacher used to say, your job is just to watch.

302
00:31:08,797 --> 00:31:09,999
Your job is just to be aware.

303
00:31:15,905 --> 00:31:17,728
Patience.

304
00:31:18,088 --> 00:31:21,012
The Buddha says this is the highest form of ascetic practice.

305
00:31:21,432 --> 00:31:33,949
So if you think of ascetic practice as, you know, fasting for long times, or in certain practices, you've seen these...

306
00:31:34,856 --> 00:32:01,809
ascetics in the east even the early christian desert ascetics you know sort of like for instance just holding up their arm in the air till it withers you've seen that one have you seen that one yeah so these sort of heavy ascetic practices he says actually the greatest of all ascetic practices is patience so patience is just a willingness to bear forbearance

307
00:32:03,156 --> 00:32:14,953
not only just our own internal pains and stuff, just not to get angry with things, not to be irritated, but of course with situations and other people.

308
00:32:16,295 --> 00:32:20,821
So that patience is one of his great virtues.

309
00:32:22,183 --> 00:32:33,078
And he gives the example of someone who says, if bandits came along and cut you from limb to limb, if at any time you felt hatred

310
00:32:33,650 --> 00:32:37,034
or a grudge against them, you would be no disciple of mine.

311
00:32:37,594 --> 00:32:41,778
That's a bit tough, isn't it?

312
00:32:41,798 --> 00:32:50,708
When I told this one, somebody said, yeah, the Buddha had a great sense of humour.

313
00:32:50,728 --> 00:32:55,053
But patience is just a great virtue, isn't it?

314
00:32:55,073 --> 00:32:58,676
Patience.

315
00:32:58,696 --> 00:32:59,397
Truthfulness.

316
00:32:59,958 --> 00:33:03,521
Here it's defined as, if you say you're going to do something, do it.

317
00:33:05,324 --> 00:33:11,031
But I mean you can stretch that also to being careful as to what you say.

318
00:33:11,071 --> 00:33:15,076
Even exaggeration is a small level of untruthfulness.

319
00:33:15,577 --> 00:33:18,080
It's not being absolutely correct.

320
00:33:19,923 --> 00:33:22,487
Exaggerating both negatively and positively.

321
00:33:26,592 --> 00:33:27,733
And then there's resolution.

322
00:33:28,034 --> 00:33:29,855
So that's what we were doing today, resolution.

323
00:33:29,895 --> 00:33:32,579
Resolution is just that real commitment.

324
00:33:32,914 --> 00:33:42,786
In the Buddha's life, it manifested in his resolution to sit under the tree and sort of work the problem out, either to the point of death or he'd actually work it out.

325
00:33:43,747 --> 00:33:46,430
So you have to be pretty resolved to do something like that.

326
00:33:53,037 --> 00:34:00,525
What I normally say is that, say a course, you come on a course, that you commit yourself to that course completely, right?

327
00:34:01,432 --> 00:34:06,057
Acceptance, you've always got to put a little ex-clause in because you might go overboard.

328
00:34:06,439 --> 00:34:10,242
Accept in emergency or extraordinary circumstance.

329
00:34:10,262 --> 00:34:13,867
And of course you're going to define extraordinary circumstance in all sorts of ways.

330
00:34:14,447 --> 00:34:23,358
But the problem with making too hard a decision is that even when all the signs are you should stop, you don't.

331
00:34:23,878 --> 00:34:25,380
And then you do yourself damage, you see.

332
00:34:26,942 --> 00:34:30,005
I know somebody who kept sitting and sitting with

333
00:34:30,204 --> 00:34:59,875
knees you know with these knees business you know and the teachers my teacher actually the Burmese would just say watch the breath you know sit just watch this you know watch the pain unfortunately she damaged her knees so you have to be you have to be slightly careful you have to go you have to really suffer if you want to damage your knees by the way you know it doesn't come with just a little bit of pain

334
00:35:00,530 --> 00:35:01,411
You've got to work at it.

335
00:35:03,514 --> 00:35:05,135
Then there's loving kindness, metta.

336
00:35:05,456 --> 00:35:15,068
The Buddha often uses metta to mean all forms of love, which includes compassion and sympathetic joy.

337
00:35:15,128 --> 00:35:21,918
Remember, rejoicing in someone, others, good fortune or success as our own.

338
00:35:22,097 --> 00:35:25,943
Don't forget, all these things have to be also directed towards ourselves.

339
00:35:28,126 --> 00:35:29,186
And then equanimity.

340
00:35:29,960 --> 00:35:59,139
all these virtues do have their obvious enemy their straight enemy and their subtle enemy so with love the obvious enemy is hatred but the more subtle enemy is attachment and you can always tell when you're coming from attachment because you tend to be not listening to the other person or not taking their view or their desire on

341
00:35:59,862 --> 00:36:26,172
and then you tend to get upset because they're not doing what you want to do you get irritated, you get bored with them, all that sort of stuff or whenever you feel negative about somebody whom, especially if you have a close relation to them then you know that's a sign of our attachment it's always coming from me rather than them or us it doesn't mean to say that

342
00:36:26,862 --> 00:36:30,126
You've got to be careful with that because you don't want to get abused.

343
00:36:31,168 --> 00:36:33,090
You've also got to take yourself into account.

344
00:36:35,313 --> 00:36:36,356
Anyway, it's a tricky area.

345
00:36:36,376 --> 00:36:39,360
I haven't got time.

346
00:36:39,380 --> 00:36:41,862
I can go on and on about that one.

347
00:36:42,043 --> 00:36:50,054
But equanimity, of course, is confusion, just to get lost in something.

348
00:36:50,416 --> 00:36:53,460
But its more subtle enemy is this indifference.

349
00:36:54,065 --> 00:36:56,188
Where you're standing away too much.

350
00:36:56,208 --> 00:36:59,934
You're standing away too much.

351
00:37:00,974 --> 00:37:02,597
There was a woman came to see me.

352
00:37:02,617 --> 00:37:09,367
She said that every time she came out of meditation at home, her partner accused her of being cold, you see.

353
00:37:10,168 --> 00:37:14,014
So I said to her, well, do you do any metta when you finish your practice?

354
00:37:14,034 --> 00:37:14,335
She said no.

355
00:37:15,597 --> 00:37:16,597
I said, well, that's what you've got to do.

356
00:37:16,657 --> 00:37:19,762
I said, you know, when you sit, you want to be cool.

357
00:37:19,782 --> 00:37:21,043
You want to be equanimous.

358
00:37:21,065 --> 00:37:21,985
You want to be distant.

359
00:37:22,025 --> 00:37:23,989
You want to be able to investigate.

360
00:37:24,750 --> 00:37:26,452
But somehow you've got to re-engage.

361
00:37:26,871 --> 00:37:28,454
You've got to re-engage with the world.

362
00:37:28,855 --> 00:37:30,557
And you do that through the practice of metta.

363
00:37:32,059 --> 00:37:33,081
Anyway, she didn't come back.

364
00:37:36,565 --> 00:37:39,630
Either he gave up on her or she practiced a bit of metta.

365
00:37:41,550 --> 00:37:47,478
So let me read out the way that it says in the commentaries.

366
00:37:47,498 --> 00:37:56,849
As a great being, so that's often a synonym for somebody who is attempting to become fully liberated.

367
00:37:58,409 --> 00:38:00,733
Or an enlightened being, yeah.

368
00:38:00,753 --> 00:38:09,262
Are concerned with the welfare of living beings, not tolerating the suffering of beings, wishing long duration to the higher states of happiness of beings.

369
00:38:09,697 --> 00:38:12,300
and being impartial and just to all beings.

370
00:38:12,460 --> 00:38:20,251
Therefore, they give alms to all beings so that they may be happy without investigating whether they are worthy or not.

371
00:38:22,213 --> 00:38:25,538
By avoiding to do them any harm, they observe morality.

372
00:38:26,177 --> 00:38:31,744
In order to bring morality to perfection, they train themselves in renunciation.

373
00:38:31,764 --> 00:38:37,291
And in order to understand clearly what is beneficial or injurious to beings, they purify their wisdom.

374
00:38:38,335 --> 00:38:42,601
For the sake of the welfare and happiness of others, they constantly exert their energy.

375
00:38:43,541 --> 00:38:50,932
Though having become heroes through utmost energy, they are nevertheless full of forbearance towards the manifold failings of beings.

376
00:38:51,594 --> 00:38:55,778
And once they have promised to give or do something, they do not break their promise.

377
00:38:56,960 --> 00:39:03,349
With unshakable resolution, they work for the will and welfare of beings.

378
00:39:03,911 --> 00:39:06,974
And with unshakable kindness, they are helpful to all,

379
00:39:07,275 --> 00:39:12,143
and by reason of their equanimity they do not expect anything in return.

380
00:39:13,286 --> 00:39:14,467
There we are.

381
00:39:14,487 --> 00:39:16,070
That's a nice little standard for us.

382
00:39:18,233 --> 00:39:27,949
So that's the, you know, just the little reflections on these paramis, these virtues or perfections that we ought to develop.

383
00:39:29,391 --> 00:39:32,135
And the other thing is commitment.

384
00:39:33,887 --> 00:39:37,612
It really is a case of committing yourself to a daily practice.

385
00:39:39,213 --> 00:39:39,695
Morning.

386
00:39:41,036 --> 00:39:43,699
It's important because that sets the weather vane.

387
00:39:43,818 --> 00:39:49,365
It sort of reminds you the level of awareness and consciousness you want to try and maintain throughout the day.

388
00:39:52,349 --> 00:40:00,077
And then to practice that loving kindness to re-engage with the world straight after that, you see.

389
00:40:00,818 --> 00:40:01,599
So that's important.

390
00:40:02,255 --> 00:40:05,097
And then in the evening, that's the other time, really.

391
00:40:06,539 --> 00:40:11,525
Specifically when you come back from work or definitely before you eat.

392
00:40:12,025 --> 00:40:13,347
After you eat, you just fall asleep.

393
00:40:14,349 --> 00:40:16,431
And the reason there is really to just sit.

394
00:40:16,652 --> 00:40:18,713
And remember, you don't always have to sit in posture.

395
00:40:19,375 --> 00:40:22,679
It is a good thing to sit in posture because it does help the awakeness.

396
00:40:23,539 --> 00:40:26,282
But there, you're just letting the day come through.

397
00:40:26,603 --> 00:40:29,967
So irritations and anxieties and all this stuff.

398
00:40:30,402 --> 00:40:54,181
things that have been happening during the day just let them arise and pass away so let them pass there's all the cleansing you see and then uh preparing for sleep that's also important you know rather than just you know coming straight off facebook launching yourself onto the pillar or some exciting you know horror movie and then you know

399
00:40:55,157 --> 00:40:57,101
I mean, you've got to prepare for sleep.

400
00:40:57,561 --> 00:41:04,971
I always think you need a half an hour where you just slow down, you can listen to beautiful music, you can practice metta.

401
00:41:06,012 --> 00:41:11,378
It's just something just to bring everything down so that when you sleep you actually have deep sleep.

402
00:41:14,302 --> 00:41:21,132
And then of course there's many times during the day when there's nothing to do, you're not doing anything.

403
00:41:21,280 --> 00:41:50,663
in the sense of you're walking upstairs or you're waiting for some transport the bus or the tube or you're hanging around waiting for a friend or there's nothing to do you're just sitting there and often what we do is we just let the mind wander it's kind of wasted time whereas there are beautiful little opportunities to practice metta or to you know some positive thought or thinking around the dharma or a particular issue or something

404
00:41:51,284 --> 00:41:52,666
But not to let the mind wander.

405
00:41:53,065 --> 00:41:55,369
That's the awful thing.

406
00:41:55,869 --> 00:41:57,030
Letting the mind wander.

407
00:41:58,052 --> 00:42:00,655
It's alright when you're in a daydream.

408
00:42:00,695 --> 00:42:06,922
But when you come out, we have to say to ourselves, now what have I been developing there?

409
00:42:07,443 --> 00:42:12,668
What horrible state of mind have I been developing in that ten minutes, half an hour?

410
00:42:13,550 --> 00:42:19,637
When I first began sitting, I'd sit for a whole hour going through it.

411
00:42:20,478 --> 00:42:47,987
one fantasy after another it's unbelievable it hasn't got that much better but i mean at least but i mean at least uh it's recognizing that the mind when when you let it go it it just is messing you up that's all and um that plum village which is a monastery in france

412
00:42:48,405 --> 00:42:55,436
It's the main center for Thich Nhat Hanh, who's a very famous teacher in the Zen tradition, Vietnamese.

413
00:42:56,297 --> 00:43:01,525
